'''Microsoft Classroom''' was an online [[blended learning]] platform for [[schools]] that aims to simplify grading assignments and student communication in a paperless way.<ref>{{cite web |title=Microsoft Classroom, a new Office 365 service for teachers and students |url=https://mspoweruser.com/microsoft-classroom-new-office-365-service-teachers-students/ |accessdate=April 27, 2017 |work=MSPoweruser |date=April 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Thurrott |first1=Paul |title=Office 365 Education is Being Updated with Microsoft Classroom, Other New Features |url=https://www.thurrott.com/cloud/office-365/66343/office-365-education-updated-microsoft-classroom-new-features |accessdate=April 27, 2017 |work=Thurrott.com |date=April 14, 2016}}</ref> It was introduced for [[Office 365 Education]] subscribers in April 2016.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Day |first1=Matt |title=Microsoft is sharpening its tools for the classroom |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/business/microsoft/microsoft-is-sharpening-its-tools-for-the-classroom/ |accessdate=April 27, 2017 |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=April 14, 2016}}</ref>

On May 18, 2017 Microsoft announced the retirement of Microsoft Classroom, which was completed on January 31, 2018. Some features of Microsoft Classroom became part of [[Microsoft Teams]] in Office 365 Education.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/4022583/microsoft-classroom-preview-features-are-moving-to-microsoft-teams |title=Microsoft Classroom Preview features are moving to Microsoft Teams in Office 365 for Education |website=Support |publisher=Microsoft |publication-date=May 17, 2017}}</ref>

